african american arts winter lecture series huey copeland african american arts winter lecture series huey copeland practicing negressity this lecture examines the negress a key figure within western artistic production of the last two centuries who takes us from the maid featured in edouard manet's olympia 1863 to the fictional hybrids populating the work of contemporary artists such as wangechi mutu kara walker and donelle woolford by remaining attentive to the phantasms that have haunted the appearance of africanist femininity as well as to black women artists ways of recasting them this paper newly frames and interprets the visual practices that have not only produced the negress but also fundamentally shaped the modern aesthetic huey copeland ph d uc berkeley 2006 is assistant professor in the department of art history and affiliated faculty in the department of african american studies at northwestern university more information date and time wednesday february 17 2010 5 00 pm approximate duration of 1.5 hour s location cummings art building ar2 map audience faculty staff general public students category lectures readings sponsor department of art & art history contact 650 723 3404 risip stanford edu admission free and open to the public download email event print use this permalink last modified february 9 2010
